---
import ProjectDetail from '../../layouts/ProjectDetail.astro';

const demoVideo = '/videos/FR Chat Demo.mp4';
---

<ProjectDetail
  title="Friends Reconnected AI Chatbot"
  description="Production Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) chatbot that scrapes a live WordPress website, indexes its content with vector embeddings, and delivers context-aware answers through a streaming conversational interface."
  tags={[
    'RAG',
    'FastAPI',
    'ChromaDB',
    'Groq',
    'Ollama',
    'Playwright',
    'WordPress',
    'Render'
  ]}
  github="https://github.com/MariamKhubashvilii/Friends-Reconnected-Chatbot"
  liveDemo="https://friendsreconnected.co.uk/chat/"
  liveDemoLabel="Live Chat"
  accent="emerald"
  demoVideo={demoVideo}
  demoPoster="/thumbnails/FR Chat Screenshot.jpeg"
>

  <section class="project-grid">

    <article class="project-card summary-card">
      <h2>Project Summary</h2>

      <p>
        Friends Reconnected AI is a production Retrieval-Augmented Generation
        (RAG) chatbot built for a UK tracing service. Instead of relying solely
        on an LLM, the application retrieves relevant information directly from
        the company's website before generating responses, reducing
        hallucinations while keeping answers grounded in real content.
      </p>

      <div class="summary-list">

        <div>
          <strong>Production-ready RAG pipeline</strong>
          <p>
            Automatically scrapes the website, chunks content, generates vector
            embeddings, stores them inside ChromaDB, retrieves the most relevant
            context and streams responses using Groq.
          </p>
        </div>

        <div>
          <strong>Live customer support</strong>
          <p>
            Embedded directly into the Friends Reconnected WordPress website,
            providing visitors with instant answers while linking back to the
            original website pages.
          </p>
        </div>

      </div>

    </article>

    <article class="project-card detail-card">
      <h2>Highlights</h2>

      <ul>
        <li>Production Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)</li>
        <li>Automatic website scraping with Playwright</li>
        <li>Persistent ChromaDB vector database</li>
        <li>Streaming responses using FastAPI SSE</li>
        <li>Confidence-based clarification workflow</li>
        <li>Source attribution for generated answers</li>
        <li>Embedded directly into WordPress</li>
      </ul>

    </article>

  </section>

  <section class="project-section">

    <div class="section-content">

      <h2>System Architecture</h2>

      <p>
        The chatbot follows a Retrieval-Augmented Generation architecture.
        Website content is periodically scraped, cleaned and chunked before
        being embedded into a persistent ChromaDB collection. At runtime, each
        user query is embedded, relevant chunks are retrieved through semantic
        similarity search and injected into the prompt sent to Groq's LLM.
      </p>

      <div class="section-grid">

        <div>

          <h3>Backend</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>FastAPI API</li>
            <li>Server-Sent Events streaming</li>
            <li>ChromaDB vector retrieval</li>
            <li>Conversation history</li>
            <li>Confidence scoring</li>
            <li>Clarification workflow</li>

          </ul>

        </div>

        <div>

          <h3>Pipeline</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Playwright website scraper</li>
            <li>BeautifulSoup HTML parsing</li>
            <li>Content cleaning & chunking</li>
            <li>Ollama embeddings</li>
            <li>Groq inference</li>
            <li>WordPress integration</li>
          </ul>

        </div>

      </div>

    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="project-section">

    <div class="section-content">

      <h2>Engineering Decisions</h2>

      <p>
        Rather than selecting tools solely based on popularity, each component
        was chosen according to deployment simplicity, development speed and
        operational cost while keeping the system production-ready.
      </p>

      <div class="section-grid">

        <div>

          <h3>Technology Choices</h3>

          <ul>
            <li><strong>Playwright</strong> — reliably renders JavaScript-heavy pages before extraction.</li>

            <li><strong>BeautifulSoup</strong> — lightweight HTML parsing after rendering.</li>

            <li><strong>ChromaDB</strong> — persistent vector storage with minimal operational overhead.</li>

            <li><strong>Groq</strong> — extremely fast inference and generous free tier.</li>

            <li><strong>FastAPI</strong> — asynchronous API with native streaming support.</li>

          </ul>

        </div>

        <div>

          <h3>Trade-offs</h3>

          <ul>

            <li>Playwright is slower than static scraping but supports dynamic websites.</li>

            <li>ChromaDB is ideal for small-to-medium datasets but isn't intended for massive distributed deployments.</li>

            <li>Local Ollama embeddings eliminate API costs but require a dedicated embedding service.</li>

            <li>Render offers simple deployment but free instances have resource limitations.</li>

          </ul>

        </div>

      </div>

    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="project-section">

    <div class="section-content">

      <h2>Request Lifecycle</h2>

      <p>
        Each user request follows a retrieval pipeline designed to maximise
        factual accuracy while maintaining low response times. Instead of asking
        the language model to answer from prior knowledge alone, the system
        first searches the vector database for the most relevant website
        content.
      </p>

      <div class="section-grid">

        <div>

          <h3>Runtime Flow</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>User sends a question from the embedded widget.</li>
            <li>The query is converted into a vector embedding.</li>
            <li>ChromaDB retrieves the most relevant content.</li>
            <li>Retrieved context is injected into the prompt.</li>
            <li>Groq streams the response token-by-token.</li>
            <li>Relevant source links are returned to the user.</li>
          </ul>

        </div>

        <div>

          <h3>Fallback Logic</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Confidence score calculated after retrieval.</li>
            <li>Low-confidence matches trigger clarification instead of guessing.</li>
            <li>Keyword matching supplements semantic retrieval.</li>
            <li>Suggested follow-up questions improve user experience.</li>
          </ul>

        </div>

      </div>

    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="project-section">

    <div class="section-content">

      <h2>Production Deployment</h2>

      <p>
        The chatbot is deployed as a production web service and embedded
        directly into the Friends Reconnected website. The frontend communicates
        with a FastAPI backend hosted on Render, while Groq performs language
        model inference and ChromaDB provides semantic retrieval.
      </p>

      <div class="section-grid">

        <div>

          <h3>Current Deployment</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Frontend embedded into WordPress.</li>
            <li>FastAPI backend hosted on Render.</li>
            <li>Persistent ChromaDB vector database.</li>
            <li>Groq LLM for response generation.</li>
            <li>Streaming responses via Server-Sent Events.</li>
          </ul>

        </div>

        <div>

          <h3>Current Development</h3>

          <ul>
            <li>Migrating embeddings to an AWS-hosted service.</li>
            <li>Separating embedding generation from the application server.</li>
            <li>Preparing the system for easier scaling and maintenance.</li>
            <li>Reducing dependency on local embedding infrastructure.</li>
          </ul>

        </div>

      </div>

    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="project-section project-usage">

    <h2>Performance & Engineering Considerations</h2>

    <p>
      The current architecture prioritises reliability, maintainability and
      deployment simplicity while leaving room for future optimisation as usage
      grows.
    </p>

    <div class="usage-card">

      <div>

        <strong>Potential Performance Improvements</strong>

        <p>
          Hybrid retrieval (BM25 + vectors), metadata filtering, reranking,
          embedding caching, improved chunking strategies and asynchronous
          ingestion can further increase retrieval quality and reduce response
          latency.
        </p>

      </div>

      <div>

        <strong>Scalability Roadmap</strong>

        <p>
          AWS-hosted embeddings, automated scheduled scraping, CI/CD,
          containerisation, monitoring, analytics and horizontal scaling are
          planned as the application evolves.
        </p>

      </div>

    </div>

  </section>

  <section class="project-section">

    <div class="section-content">

      <h2>What This Project Demonstrates</h2>

      <p>
        Beyond building a chatbot, this project demonstrates end-to-end system
        design across data ingestion, semantic search, backend development,
        deployment and user experience. It combines modern LLM tooling with
        production-oriented engineering decisions, focusing on accuracy,
        maintainability and scalable architecture rather than simply connecting
        an API to a language model.
      </p>

    </div>

  </section>

</ProjectDetail>